ns in microtask queue. Let me trace through more carefully...\n\nActually, `emit` is `async`, so even though it starts executing synchronously, the `for` loop with `await handler(payload)` runs in the async context. When we call `void bus.emit(...)`, JavaScript will start executing `emit` synchronously up to the first `await`. Since handlers are synchronous, `await handler(payload)` wraps the result in a resolved promise and resumes after microtask. So the first handler will be called synchronously, but subsequent handlers and the rest of the function execute as microtasks.\n\nWait no - `async function emit() { ... await handler(payload); ... }` - the first `await` causes the function to return a promise and yields control. So even the first handler call after `await` happens in a microtask, not synchronously.\n\nActually, I need to re-read. In an async function, code before the first `await` runs synchronously. So `this.eventLog.push(...)` runs synchronously, then `await handler(payload)` - the handler IS called, but the result is awaited. If the handler is sync and returns `void` (undefined), `await undefined` wraps it as `Promise.resolve(undefined)` and yields.\n\nSo: `eventLog.push` is sync, then `handler(payload)` IS called synchronously for the first handler, but after that handler returns, `await` yields. This means the first handler of each event type runs synchronously when `emit` is called, but subsequent handlers run asynchronously.\n\nThis is complex. The simplest fix: make the services that need synchronous operation not rely on `void bus.emit()` for anything critical. But for the tests, I need to ensure events are processed. Let me adjust the test to be async-aware, and also ensure the analytics product tracking doesn't rely on a separate handler registration.\n\nLet me consolidate the analytics ORDER_CREATED handlers into one, and fix the tests."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1874,"ca